SUMMARY:Ostrom Workshop | Research Series: Yaron Weissberg
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;Bio  Yaron Weissberg is a Postdoctoral Researcher at t
 he Research Group for International Politics and Conflict Research. He ho
 lds a Bachelor's degree in Political Economy from the University of Lucer
 ne and a Master's degree in Comparative and International Studies from ET
 H Z├╝rich and the University of Z├╝rich. He completed his Ph.D. at ETH Z├
 ╝rich's International Conflict Research Group\, focusing on the intersect
 ion of natural resources and conflict. His research examines how the tran
 sition to cleaner forms of energy can reduce risks associated with resour
 ce-based conflicts\, while also exploring new risks that might emerge.Tit
 le  Digging Out of Trouble? The Development Potential of Green Minerals i
 n Conflict-Affected RegionsAbstract  The global transition to renewable e
 nergy requires substantial increases in green technology mineral (GTM) ex
 traction\, including lithium\, cobalt\, and graphite. While mineral wealt
 h may fuel conflict\, resources can also provide employment during violen
 ce and revenues for post-conflict reconstruction. This paper examines whe
 ther GTMs exhibit such stabilizing characteristics in conflict-affected r
 egions. We argue that GTMs differ fundamentally from "traditional" confli
 ct resources. Unlike oil and diamonds\, GTMs lack concentrated value to g
 enerate large revenues for armed actors during conflict. Furthermore\, th
 eir bulky nature requires substantial infrastructure investments\, creati
 ng local economic spillovers that benefit the local economy and populatio
 n more broadly. However\, GTM extraction remains highly vulnerable to lar
 ge-scale conflict due to infrastructure dependence and insufficient reven
 ues for firms to justify continued operations under extreme insecurity. U
 sing PRIO-GRID data and UCDP conflict measures for the post-Cold War peri
 od\, we analyze spatial variation in mining activity and nighttime light 
 emissions across conflict intensities. We find that GTM sites demonstrate
  economic resilience during localized violence but experience severe disr
 uption during civil wars\, with substantial variation by extraction mode.
  These findings clarify conditions under which resource extraction econom
 ically stabilizes rather than destabilizes conflict-affected regions\, co
 ntributing to our understanding of the green energy transition's security
  implications.About the Ostrom Workshop Research Series  Learn about inno
 vative research by Graduate Students and Visiting Scholars as they advanc
 e the mission of the Ostrom Workshop\, building upon the theme of governa
 nce to understand and address major societal problems.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  &#160\;</p><p><strong><picture class="l
 w_image lw_image30276  lw_align_left lw_block"><source type="image/webp" 
 srcset="https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/2x/gid/105/width/300/heigh
 t/200/30276_yaron_weissberg.webp 2x\, https://events.iu.edu/live/image/sc
 ale/3x/gid/105/width/300/height/200/30276_yaron_weissberg.webp 3x" data-o
 rigin="responsive"/><source type="image/jpeg" srcset="https://events.iu.e
 du/live/image/scale/2x/gid/105/width/300/height/200/30276_yaron_weissberg
 .rev.1772207404.jpg 2x\, https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/3x/gid/10
 5/width/300/height/200/30276_yaron_weissberg.rev.1772207404.jpg 3x" data-
 origin="responsive"/><img width="300" height="200" alt="" data-alt="" dat
 a-decoration="true" src="https://events.iu.edu/live/image/gid/105/width/3
 00/height/200/30276_yaron_weissberg.rev.1772207404.jpg" title="yaron weis
 sberg" srcset="https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/2x/gid/105/width/30
 0/height/200/30276_yaron_weissberg.rev.1772207404.jpg 2x\, https://events
 .iu.edu/live/image/scale/3x/gid/105/width/300/height/200/30276_yaron_weis
 sberg.rev.1772207404.jpg 3x" data-max-w="1024" data-max-h="683" loading="
 lazy" data-optimized="true"/></picture>Bio</strong></p><p>  Yaron Weissbe
 rg is a Postdoctoral Researcher at the Research Group for International P
 olitics and Conflict Research. He holds a Bachelor's degree in Political 
 Economy from the University of Lucerne and a Master's degree in Comparati
 ve and International Studies from ETH Z├╝rich and the University of Z├╝ri
 ch. He completed his Ph.D. at ETH Z├╝rich's International Conflict Resear
 ch Group\, focusing on the intersection of natural resources and conflict
 . His research examines how the transition to cleaner forms of energy can
  reduce risks associated with resource-based conflicts\, while also explo
 ring new risks that might emerge.</p><p><strong>Title</strong></p><p>  Di
 gging Out of Trouble? The Development Potential of Green Minerals in Conf
 lict-Affected Regions</p><p><strong>Abstract</strong></p><p>  The global 
 transition to renewable energy requires substantial increases in green te
 chnology mineral (GTM) extraction\, including lithium\, cobalt\, and grap
 hite. While mineral wealth may fuel conflict\, resources can also provide
  employment during violence and revenues for post-conflict reconstruction
 . This paper examines whether GTMs exhibit such stabilizing characteristi
 cs in conflict-affected regions. We argue that GTMs differ fundamentally 
 from "traditional" conflict resources. Unlike oil and diamonds\, GTMs lac
 k concentrated value to generate large revenues for armed actors during c
 onflict. Furthermore\, their bulky nature requires substantial infrastruc
 ture investments\, creating local economic spillovers that benefit the lo
 cal economy and population more broadly. However\, GTM extraction remains
  highly vulnerable to large-scale conflict due to infrastructure dependen
 ce and insufficient revenues for firms to justify continued operations un
 der extreme insecurity. Using PRIO-GRID data and UCDP conflict measures f
 or the post-Cold War period\, we analyze spatial variation in mining acti
 vity and nighttime light emissions across conflict intensities. We find t
 hat GTM sites demonstrate economic resilience during localized violence b
 ut experience severe disruption during civil wars\, with substantial vari
 ation by extraction mode. These findings clarify conditions under which r
 esource extraction economically stabilizes rather than destabilizes confl
 ict-affected regions\, contributing to our understanding of the green ene
 rgy transition's security implications.</p><p><strong>About the Ostrom Wo
 rkshop Research Series</strong></p><p>  Learn about innovative research b
 y Graduate Students and Visiting Scholars as they advance the mission of 
 the Ostrom Workshop\, building upon the theme of governance to understand
  and address major societal problems.</p>
