SUMMARY:Ostrom Workshop | Research Series: Jorge Canabal
DESCRIPTION:Bio  Jorge Acevedo Canabal\, MD\, is a visiting scholar at th
 e Ostrom Workshop and co-Principal Investigator of the "Team Building for
  the Cyber-Epidemiology Center" project\, which receives funding from an 
 IU 2030 Emerging Frontiers Grant. His past relevant work involves clinica
 l medicine and research focused on novel pathogens and vulnerable populat
 ions\, disaster response\, healthcare crises response\, and cybersecurity
  in healthcare.Title  Counting the Invisible: Expansion and Application o
 f Technological Hazards' Classification to Document Human Harm in Healthc
 are\, Public Health\, and BeyondAbstract  Despite growing reliance on dig
 ital technologies and connected devices to improve public safety\, public
  health\, and healthcare delivery\, there exists an identified but not co
 mprehensively described gap in the classification and documentation of fa
 ilure modes that can result in human harm. This gap is notable precisely 
 because external cause documentation frameworks in vital statistics and c
 linical settings are not new: existing tools successfully capture harm at
 tributable to natural disasters such as hurricanes\, floods\, and earthqu
 akes. It is in the specific domain of technological hazards involving dig
 ital systems that the most significant classificatory gaps remain. These 
 failure modes can be broadly described as accidental\, adversarial\, or a
 s the result of cascading effects of failures in the infrastructure upon 
 which the system of interest relies.  During this talk\, the presenter wi
 ll discuss (1) how adoption and adaptation of existing frameworks and too
 ls from several fields of study\, including epidemiology\, health informa
 tics\, and patient safety science\, can support the development of cross-
 disciplinary functional definitions\; (2) how adaptation of Ostrom's IAD 
 framework can be useful for systematically identifying\, at different lev
 els of observation\, relevant feedback loops that can inform targeted res
 ponses\; and (3) challenges that must be addressed for the development an
 d implementation of applied research that improves current understanding 
 of technological failures' relationship to human harm\, and that can info
 rm further development of technologies and interventions that mitigate ri
 sk.About the Ostrom Workshop Research Series  Learn about innovative rese
 arch by Graduate Students and Visiting Scholars as they advance the missi
 on of the Ostrom Workshop\, building upon the theme of governance to unde
 rstand and address major societal problems.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><picture class="lw_image lw_image28003 lw
 _align_left lw_block"><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://events.iu
 .edu/live/image/gid/105/width/200/height/200/28003_jorgecanabal.webp 1x" 
 data-origin="responsive"/><source type="image/jpeg" srcset="https://event
 s.iu.edu/live/image/gid/105/width/200/height/200/28003_jorgecanabal.rev.1
 757008139.jpg 1x" data-origin="responsive"/><img width="200" height="200"
  alt="" data-alt="" data-decoration="true" src="https://events.iu.edu/liv
 e/image/gid/105/width/200/height/200/28003_jorgecanabal.rev.1757008139.jp
 g" data-max-w="200" data-max-h="200" loading="lazy" data-optimized="true"
 /></picture></p><p><strong>Bio</strong></p><p>  Jorge Acevedo Canabal\, M
 D\, is a visiting scholar at the Ostrom Workshop and co-Principal Investi
 gator of the "Team Building for the Cyber-Epidemiology Center" project\, 
 which receives funding from an IU 2030 Emerging Frontiers Grant. His past
  relevant work involves clinical medicine and research focused on novel p
 athogens and vulnerable populations\, disaster response\, healthcare cris
 es response\, and cybersecurity in healthcare.</p><p><strong>Title</stron
 g></p><p>  Counting the Invisible: Expansion and Application of Technolog
 ical Hazards' Classification to Document Human Harm in Healthcare\, Publi
 c Health\, and Beyond</p><p><strong>Abstract</strong></p><p>  Despite gro
 wing reliance on digital technologies and connected devices to improve pu
 blic safety\, public health\, and healthcare delivery\, there exists an i
 dentified but not comprehensively described gap in the classification and
  documentation of failure modes that can result in human harm. This gap i
 s notable precisely because external cause documentation frameworks in vi
 tal statistics and clinical settings are not new: existing tools successf
 ully capture harm attributable to natural disasters such as hurricanes\, 
 floods\, and earthquakes. It is in the specific domain of technological h
 azards involving digital systems that the most significant classificatory
  gaps remain. These failure modes can be broadly described as accidental\
 , adversarial\, or as the result of cascading effects of failures in the 
 infrastructure upon which the system of interest relies.</p><p>  During t
 his talk\, the presenter will discuss (1) how adoption and adaptation of 
 existing frameworks and tools from several fields of study\, including ep
 idemiology\, health informatics\, and patient safety science\, can suppor
 t the development of cross-disciplinary functional definitions\; (2) how 
 adaptation of Ostrom's IAD framework can be useful for systematically ide
 ntifying\, at different levels of observation\, relevant feedback loops t
 hat can inform targeted responses\; and (3) challenges that must be addre
 ssed for the development and implementation of applied research that impr
 oves current understanding of technological failures' relationship to hum
 an harm\, and that can inform further development of technologies and int
 erventions that mitigate risk.</p><p><strong>About the Ostrom Workshop Re
 search Series</strong></p><p>  Learn about innovative research by Graduat
 e Students and Visiting Scholars as they advance the mission of the Ostro
 m Workshop\, building upon the theme of governance to understand and addr
 ess major societal problems.</p>
