SUMMARY:21JPSI/IKS: "From Manners to Rules: Advocating for Legalism in So
 uth Korea and Japan" (Prof. Celeste Arrington\, GWU)
DESCRIPTION:This public event is open to all students\, faculty\, staff\,
  and members of the community. Please join us! Professor Arrington's prep
 ared remarks will be followed by a discussion/audience Q&amp\;A. Co-hoste
 d with HLS' Institute for Korean Studies\, and co-sponsored by the Depart
 ment of Political Science and the Maurer School of Law's Stewart Center o
 n the Global Legal Profession.About the talk:  Persons with disabilities 
 have gained new rights and access in the past few decades in Japan and So
 uth Korea. Laws and regulations related to disabled persons have become m
 ore detailed and enforceable\, and policymaking processes increasingly in
 clude persons with disabilities. Celeste Arrington unpacks how the demand
  for law is driving these advances in disability rights. By advocating fo
 r legislative changes and creatively using them\, including through the c
 ourts\, activists and lawyers are reshaping regulatory style and forging 
 new opportunities for political engagement. The legalistic turn in disabi
 lity-related policy marks a significant change in Japan and Korea\, where
  officials relied on nonbinding guidelines\, bureaucratic discretion\, an
 d vague laws. This talk draws on Arrington's new book\, From Manners to R
 ules: Advocating for Legalism in South Korea and Japan (https://www.cambr
 idge.org/core/books/from-manners-to-rules/F68A14FC5E643B2FE1DF3708EDAD4D7
 9) (Cambridge\, 2025).About the speaker:                      Professor C
 eleste Arrington (https://elliott.gwu.edu/celeste-arrington) specializes 
 in comparative politics\, with a regional focus on the Koreas and Japan. 
 Her research interests include law and social change\, governance\, civil
  society\, social movements\, policy-making processes\, lawyers\, the med
 ia and politics\, and qualitative methods. She is also interested in the 
 international relations and security of Northeast Asia and transnational 
 activism.                                        Professor Arrington is d
 irector of the GW Institute for Korean Studies (GWIKS) and co-director of
  the East Asia National Resources Center. She is also a Visiting Research
  Scholar at Princeton's School of Public and International Affairs and a 
 faculty affiliate of the Global Japan Lab. Arrington received a Ph.D. fro
 m the University of California\, Berkeley\, an MPhil from the University 
 of Cambridge\, and an A.B. summa cum laude from Princeton University. She
  has been a fellow at Harvard\, the Institute for Advanced Study in Princ
 eton\, the Law and Public Affairs Program at Princeton\, and the Ludwig-M
 aximilians-University in Munich. GW's Office of the Vice President for Re
 search awarded her the 2021 Early Career Research Scholar Award. Her arti
 cle with Claudia Kim won the 2023 Asian Law and Society Association's dis
 tinguished article award.                  This event is made possible th
 anks to generous financial support from the Japan Foundation. All 21JPSI 
 events are 100% in-person unless otherwise noted.          &#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  This public event is open to all studen
 ts\, faculty\, staff\, and members of the community. Please join us! Prof
 essor Arrington's prepared remarks will be followed by a discussion/audie
 nce Q&amp\;A. <em>Co-hosted with HLS' Institute for Korean Studies\, and 
 co-sponsored by the Department of Political Science and the Maurer School
  of Law's Stewart Center on the Global Legal Profession.</em></p><p><span
  style="text-decoration: underline\;"><strong>About the talk:</strong></s
 pan></p><p class="x_MsoNormal" data-olk-copy-source="MessageBody">  Perso
 ns with disabilities have gained new rights and access in the past few de
 cades in Japan and South Korea. Laws and regulations related to disabled 
 persons have become more detailed and enforceable\, and policymaking proc
 esses increasingly include persons with disabilities. Celeste Arrington u
 npacks how the demand for law is driving these advances in disability rig
 hts. By advocating for legislative changes and creatively using them\, in
 cluding through the courts\, activists and lawyers are reshaping regulato
 ry style and forging new opportunities for political engagement. The lega
 listic turn in disability-related policy marks a significant change in Ja
 pan and Korea\, where officials relied on nonbinding guidelines\, bureauc
 ratic discretion\, and vague laws. This talk draws on Arrington's new boo
 k\, <i><a href="https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/from-manners-to-rule
 s/F68A14FC5E643B2FE1DF3708EDAD4D79" target="_blank" rel="noopener">From M
 anners to Rules: Advocating for Legalism in South Korea and Japan</a></i>
  (Cambridge\, 2025).</p><div class="c-vertical-tabs" data-ms-component="v
 ertical-tabs" data-vertical-tabs-display="vertical"><div class="c-vertica
 l-tabs__item" data-vertical-tabs-component="tab" data-vertical-tabs-state
 ="is-open"><div class="c-vertical-tabs__content vertical-tabs__content-lo
 ng open" data-vertical-tabs-component="content" aria-hidden="false" id="c
 ollapsible-1" role="region"><div class="s-wysiwyg"><div class="s-wysiwyg"
 ></div><div class="s-wysiwyg"><strong><span style="text-decoration: under
 line\;">About the speaker:</span></strong></div><div class="s-wysiwyg"><d
 iv class="gw-person-header"><div class="container px-0"><div class="row">
 <div class="col-md-8 col-12"><div class="person-info"><p class="person-ti
 tle">                      Professor <a href="https://elliott.gwu.edu/cel
 este-arrington" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Celeste Arrington</a> spec
 ializes in comparative politics\, with a regional focus on the Koreas and
  Japan. Her research interests include law and social change\, governance
 \, civil society\, social movements\, policy-making processes\, lawyers\,
  the media and politics\, and qualitative methods. She is also interested
  in the international relations and security of Northeast Asia and transn
 ational activism.                    </p></div></div></div></div></div><d
 iv class="container px-0"><div class="row one-column"><div class="col"><d
 iv class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-field-gw-person-biogr
 aphy field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><p>  
                   Professor Arrington is director of the GW Institute for
  Korean Studies (GWIKS) and co-director of the East Asia National Resourc
 es Center. She is also a Visiting Research Scholar at Princeton's School 
 of Public and International Affairs and a faculty affiliate of the Global
  Japan Lab. Arrington received a Ph.D. from the University of California\
 , Berkeley\, an MPhil from the University of Cambridge\, and an A.B. summ
 a cum laude from Princeton University. She has been a fellow at Harvard\,
  the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton\, the Law and Public Affai
 rs Program at Princeton\, and the Ludwig-Maximilians-University in Munich
 . GW's Office of the Vice President for Research awarded her the 2021 Ear
 ly Career Research Scholar Award. Her article with Claudia Kim won the 20
 23 Asian Law and Society Association's distinguished article award.      
             </p></div></div></div></div></div><div><em>This event is made
  possible thanks to generous financial support from the Japan Foundation.
  All 21JPSI events are 100% in-person unless otherwise noted.</em></div><
