LOCATION:GISB - Room Number: 3067
SUMMARY:Taming the Beast? Creative Destruction\, Free Speech and Social M
 edia in Central Europe
DESCRIPTION:Intricate legal challenges are posed globally by the platform
  economy\, particularly concerning regulation\, human rights\, and the es
 sential functions of the state in the 21st century. A surge of regulatory
  efforts at both national and international levels is apparent in respons
 e to the rapid digitalization and the proliferation of disruptive technol
 ogies. This phenomenon is exemplified by the General Data Protection Regu
 lation (GDPR)\, the Digital Markets Act (DMA)\, and the Digital Services 
 Act (DSA) within the European Union ŌĆō commonly referred to stateside as
  by-products of the "Brussels Effect"\, and counteracted ŌĆō most recentl
 y ŌĆō by U.S. state-led initiatives\, earning this movement the name "Tex
 as Effect" in key areas that affect the First Amendment.  Driven by this 
 development\, it makes sense to investigate the evolving relationship bet
 ween technology (herein dubbed 'the Beast') and state sovereignty. As dig
 ital platforms transcend traditional boundaries\, they challenge the stat
 e's ability to regulate effectively\, necessitating a reevaluation of wha
 t constitutes essential state functions. This reevaluation is crucial to 
 ensure that states can uphold their foundational roles\, including the pr
 otection of human rights\, maintenance of public order\, even national se
 curity\, and regulation of economic activities. Furthermore\, the concept
  of 'essential state functions' in the context of the platform economy ne
 eds to be addressed. Certain functions\, such as the administration of ju
 stice\, national defense and security\, and public health\, remain the ex
 clusive domain of the state (in the context of European integration)\, ev
 en amidst widespread digitalization on a European level. However\, the ri
 se of powerful digital platforms challenges the states' capacity to perfo
 rm these functions effectively\, prompting a need for regulatory innovati
 ons that reaffirm state authority and responsibility.  In a European cont
 ext\, most of Central Europe\, with a post-Soviet past\, is in a special 
 situation when it comes to assessing issues of sovereignty and free expre
 ssion in light of globalization and European integration. Due to the appa
 rent tension between the inherent drivers of the digital platform ecosyst
 emŌĆösuch as innovation (as the source of 'Creative Destruction') and mar
 ket expansionŌĆöand the regulatory solutions established by some states w
 ill be examined\, underscoring the need for a balanced approach that leav
 es room for innovation while safeguarding the common good\, various publi
 c interests\, and human rights\, at times with special focus on protected
  groups such as children ŌĆō "in order to secure the blessings of liberty
  to our posterity" ŌĆō a goal also echoed by the preamble of the U.S. Con
 stitution.  M├Īrton Sulyok is a Senior Lecturer at the Institute of Publi
 c Law at the University of Szeged (Hungary) and the Head of the Public La
 w Center at the MCC Law School in Budapest (Hungary). He currently sits o
 n the Board of the European Public Law Organization and is a member of th
 e European Group of Public Law. His research interests include constituti
 onal law and theory\, with special focus on constitutional interpretation
 \; European human rights law with special focus on privacy and due proces
 s protections\; law and technology\; and the concept of constitutional id
 entity in EU integration and the role of the EU Charter of Fundamental Ri
 ghts in national constitutional jurisdictions in Europe.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Intricate legal challenges are posed gl
 obally by the platform economy\, particularly concerning regulation\, hum
 an rights\, and the essential functions of the state in the 21st century.
  A surge of regulatory efforts at both national and international levels 
 is apparent in response to the rapid digitalization and the proliferation
  of disruptive technologies. This phenomenon is exemplified by the Genera
 l Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)\, the Digital Markets Act (DMA)\, and
  the Digital Services Act (DSA) within the European Union ŌĆō commonly re
 ferred to stateside as by-products of the "Brussels Effect"\, and counter
 acted ŌĆō most recently ŌĆō by U.S. state-led initiatives\, earning this 
 movement the name "Texas Effect" in key areas that affect the First Amend
 ment.</p><p>  Driven by this development\, it makes sense to investigate 
 the evolving relationship between technology (herein dubbed 'the Beast') 
 and state sovereignty. As digital platforms transcend traditional boundar
 ies\, they challenge the state's ability to regulate effectively\, necess
 itating a reevaluation of what constitutes essential state functions. Thi
 s reevaluation is crucial to ensure that states can uphold their foundati
 onal roles\, including the protection of human rights\, maintenance of pu
 blic order\, even national security\, and regulation of economic activiti
 es. Furthermore\, the concept of 'essential state functions' in the conte
 xt of the platform economy needs to be addressed. Certain functions\, suc
 h as the administration of justice\, national defense and security\, and 
 public health\, remain the exclusive domain of the state (in the context 
 of European integration)\, even amidst widespread digitalization on a Eur
 opean level. However\, the rise of powerful digital platforms challenges 
 the states' capacity to perform these functions effectively\, prompting a
  need for regulatory innovations that reaffirm state authority and respon
 sibility.</p><p>  In a European context\, most of Central Europe\, with a
  post-Soviet past\, is in a special situation when it comes to assessing 
 issues of sovereignty and free expression in light of globalization and E
 uropean integration. Due to the apparent tension between the inherent dri
 vers of the digital platform ecosystemŌĆösuch as innovation (as the sourc
 e of 'Creative Destruction') and market expansionŌĆöand the regulatory so
 lutions established by some states will be examined\, underscoring the ne
 ed for a balanced approach that leaves room for innovation while safeguar
 ding the common good\, various public interests\, and human rights\, at t
 imes with special focus on protected groups such as children ŌĆō "in orde
 r to secure the blessings of liberty to our posterity" ŌĆō a goal also ec
 hoed by the preamble of the U.S. Constitution.</p><p>  M├Īrton Sulyok is 
 a Senior Lecturer at the Institute of Public Law at the University of Sze
 ged (Hungary) and the Head of the Public Law Center at the MCC Law School
  in Budapest (Hungary). He currently sits on the Board of the European Pu
 blic Law Organization and is a member of the European Group of Public Law
 . His research interests include constitutional law and theory\, with spe
 cial focus on constitutional interpretation\; European human rights law w
 ith special focus on privacy and due process protections\; law and techno
 logy\; and the concept of constitutional identity in EU integration and t
 he role of the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights in national constitutiona
 l jurisdictions in Europe.</p>
