  work to explain why obfuscation was chosen as a strategy and why these p
 articular designs were pursued over potentially more effective alternativ
 es. Turning to the contemporary landscape of generative AI and large lang
 uage models\, where privacy threats have intensified\, it asks whether ne
 w technologies create opportunities to extend the ethical and practical s
 uccesses of earlier efforts while addressing their limitations.</p><p><st
 rong data-olk-copy-source="MessageBody">About the Speaker</strong></p><p>
 <strong data-olk-copy-source="MessageBody"><img src="https://nissenbaum.t  ech.cornell.edu/helen3.jpg" alt="" loading="lazy"/></strong></p><p>  A Pr
 ofessor of Information Science and the founding director of the Digital L
 ife Initiative at Cornell Tech. Her research spans issues of bias\, trust
