DTSTART:20260406T200000Z
DTEND:20260406T210000Z
LOCATION:355 N. Eagleson Avenue - Room Number: 1060
SUMMARY:Spring 2026 Colloquium Series with Carlos Colmenares Gil
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies is proud 
 to present the continuation of its Colloquium Series for Spring 2026.  We
  welcome Dr. Carlos Colmenares Gil&#160\;as he presents Miguel James and 
 the "Angelitos Negros" of Venezuelan Poetry.  This presentation examines 
 Venezuelan-Trinidadian poet Miguel James' oeuvre as critical of a nationa
 l project of racial democracy in Venezuela\, and of how such a project in
 forms structures of literary reception by limiting them. In a country whe
 re both political and cultural discourse frame and construct a Venezuelan
  identity as a seemingly flexible mestizaje\, James' work demands taking 
 a step back from it and articulating these heterogeneous cultural and soc
 ial elements otherwise. James' seemingly multiculturalist enumerations an
 d mixture of referents move away from a radical critique\; instead\, they
  offer a counterpoint where mestizaje as a demagogic identity is displace
 d in favor of a process of amefricanidade\, as theorized by L├®lia Gonz├Ī
 lez\, in which blackness is neither monumentalized in an immemorial past\
 , nor dissolved in a postracial present. To understand this transition fr
 om one socio-political structure of meaning to another\, Stuart Hall's co
 ncept of articulation will be key to illuminating James' poetry.&#160\;  
 &#160\;Carlos Colmenares Gil studies the Spanish-Caribbean\, continental 
 Caribbean\, and Brazil\, specifically how the cultural expressions (liter
 ature\, film\, music) from these areas are immersed\, or resist to be imm
 ersed\, in a cosmopolitan logic which translates and creates a simplified
  structure of critical reception for them. His work engages with a long t
 radition of Latin American thought as well as continental philosophy\, ps
 ychoanalysis\, and anthropology\, examining questions of high and low art
 \, the idea of the popular\, the hyper and translocal\, and the intellect
 ual life of minoritized subjects. He has published on social theorist Ale
 jandro Moreno and on Afro-Venezuelan music. Currently\, he is working on 
 a book project focused on Venezuelan poetry and the critique of interiori
 ty\; and a long essay centered around Igor Barreto and the destruction an
 d re-composition of the landscape in relation to other Latin American poe
 ts. In parallel\, he continues to research on Afro-Latin drums and the vo
 ices and chants that accompany them.        &#160\;        The CLACS Spri
 ng 2026 Colloquium meets Mondays from February through April\, with facul
 ty and guest speakers engaging Latin America and the Caribbean through re
 search on history\, culture\, language\, politics\, and the arts. Check t
 he CLACS Calendar (https://events.iu.edu/clacs/) for details.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The Center for Latin American and Carib
 bean Studies is proud to present the continuation of its <strong>Colloqui
 um Series for Spring 2026</strong>.</p><p>  We welcome <strong>Dr. Carlos
  Colmenares Gil</strong>&#160\;as he presents <em><strong>Miguel James an
 d the "Angelitos Negros" of Venezuelan Poetry.</strong></em></p><p>  This
  presentation examines Venezuelan-Trinidadian poet Miguel James' oeuvre a
 s critical of a national project of racial democracy in Venezuela\, and o
 f how such a project informs structures of literary reception by limiting
  them. In a country where both political and cultural discourse frame and
  construct a Venezuelan identity as a seemingly flexible mestizaje\, Jame
 s' work demands taking a step back from it and articulating these heterog
 eneous cultural and social elements otherwise. James' seemingly multicult
 uralist enumerations and mixture of referents move away from a radical cr
 itique\; instead\, they offer a counterpoint where mestizaje as a demagog
 ic identity is displaced in favor of a process of amefricanidade\, as the
 orized by L├®lia Gonz├Īlez\, in which blackness is neither monumentalized
  in an immemorial past\, nor dissolved in a postracial present. To unders
 tand this transition from one socio-political structure of meaning to ano
 ther\, Stuart Hall's concept of articulation will be key to illuminating 
 James' poetry.&#160\;</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p><strong>Carlos Colmenares Gil
 </strong> studies the Spanish-Caribbean\, continental Caribbean\, and Bra
 zil\, specifically how the cultural expressions (literature\, film\, musi
 c) from these areas are immersed\, or resist to be immersed\, in a cosmop
 olitan logic which translates and creates a simplified structure of criti
 cal reception for them. His work engages with a long tradition of Latin A
 merican thought as well as continental philosophy\, psychoanalysis\, and 
 anthropology\, examining questions of high and low art\, the idea of the 
 popular\, the hyper and translocal\, and the intellectual life of minorit
 ized subjects. He has published on social theorist Alejandro Moreno and o
 n Afro-Venezuelan music. Currently\, he is working on a book project focu
 sed on Venezuelan poetry and the critique of interiority\; and a long ess
 ay centered around Igor Barreto and the destruction and re-composition of
  the landscape in relation to other Latin American poets. In parallel\, h
 e continues to research on Afro-Latin drums and the voices and chants tha
 t accompany them.</p><div class="layout"><div class="full-width"><div cla
 ss="text" xmlns:jx="jsx"><p>        &#160\;      </p></div></div></div><p
 >  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium meets Mondays from February through A
 pril\, with faculty and guest speakers engaging Latin America and the Car
 ibbean through research on history\, culture\, language\, politics\, and 
 the arts. Check the <a href="https://events.iu.edu/clacs/">CLACS Calendar
 </a> for details.</p><p><picture class="lw_image lw_image30144  lw_align_
