SUMMARY:Ostrom Workshop | Research Series: Paulo Ramos
DESCRIPTION:Bio  Paulo Ramos is born from the womb of his mother\, Terezi
 nha Ramos de Jesus. He is an Afro-Brazilian visual artist\, performer\, a
 ctor\, and poet whose multidisciplinarywork spans video\, performance\, a
 nd poetry. His acclaimed poetry book\, Corpos d'├Īgua\, was published in 
 2023 in Brazil. And in 2026\, the book\, titled Bodies of Water\, will be
  released in the United States\, in English\, by NP-PRESS and Counterpath
  Press. Ramos' compelling performance piece\, presented at the 12th At Fi
 rst Sigh New Works Festival Indiana University and in venues across S├Żo 
 Paulo and Tepoztl├Īn\, gave rise to the thought-provoking videoperformanc
 e Bodies of Water: Threebuckets: a river\, a mangrow\, and a sean. Paulo 
 Ramos is a Ph.D. in Social Science in Gender and Black Studies in PUCSP. 
 Pontif├Łcia Universidade Cat├│lica de S├Żo Paulo\,Paulo Ramos continues t
 o explore and amplify the narratives of Afro-Brazilian identity.Abstract 
  Bodies of Water is an artistic performance\, an academic confrontation g
 rounded in the studies of Denise Ferreira da Silva (2020)\, constructed t
 hrough a poetic pathway in which the body becomes theoretical expansion. 
 According to Denise Ferreira da Silva\, anticolonial art must be a confro
 ntation.  Bodies of Water: A Hybrid Cartography Flowing into an etnograph
 yWE is part of my doctoral research\, built from the memory\, orality\, a
 nd ancestry of Black women who turn their daily notes into the reinventio
 n of life in community. This reinvention constitutes their intellectual p
 roduction\, naming everything that inhabits space or emerges from the way
 s they experience the worldŌĆöone that is crossed by race\, class\, and t
 he environmental. It concerns the relationship between water and Black wo
 men-mothers as a way of thinking existence\, both as a site of escape and
  of resistance.  Here\, I propose to reflect from a fieldwork perspective
  that traverses my own selfŌĆönot through an autoethnographic method\, bu
 t immersed in an etnographyWE\, a new theory in development for thinking 
 about the women and the waters that came before me.  Thus\, Bodies of Wat
 er brings forth tension\, discomfort\, and a critiCREATIVE approach devel
 oped alongside my research on my grandmother\, my mother\, my aunt\, and 
 the watersŌĆöand on environmental racism (Costa 2022\; Pacheco 2012). Bod
 ies of Water is bodyŌĆōtimeŌĆōspace poetry. Above all\, it is confrontati
 on. It is a profound dialogue between the Black body and waterŌĆöliving e
 lements\, yet constrained by the violence imposed by temporality.  Ancest
 rality and Afropessimism are both present here\, navigating together in t
 he same vessel through the currents of the Black body (Pinho 2021\; Smith
  2015)\; between these two concepts\, ecology emerges as the missing link
  that connects them.About the Ostrom Workshop Research Series  Learn abou
 t innovative research by Graduate Students and Visiting Scholars as they 
 advance the mission of the Ostrom Workshop\, building upon the theme of g
 overnance to understand and address major societal problems.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<picture class="lw_image lw_image30307  lw_a
 lign_left lw_block"><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://events.iu.e
 du/live/image/scale/2x/gid/105/width/300/height/399/30307_PauloRamosPhoto
 .webp 2x\, https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/3x/gid/105/width/300/he
 ight/399/30307_PauloRamosPhoto.webp 3x" data-origin="responsive"/><source
  type="image/jpeg" srcset="https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/2x/gid/
 105/width/300/height/399/30307_PauloRamosPhoto.rev.1772474109.jpg 2x\, ht
 tps://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/3x/gid/105/width/300/height/399/3030
 7_PauloRamosPhoto.rev.1772474109.jpg 3x" data-origin="responsive"/><img w
 idth="300" height="399" alt="" data-alt="" data-decoration="true" src="ht
 tps://events.iu.edu/live/image/gid/105/width/300/height/399/30307_PauloRa
 mosPhoto.rev.1772474109.jpg" srcset="https://events.iu.edu/live/image/sca
 le/2x/gid/105/width/300/height/399/30307_PauloRamosPhoto.rev.1772474109.j
 pg 2x\, https://events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/3x/gid/105/width/300/heigh
 t/399/30307_PauloRamosPhoto.rev.1772474109.jpg 3x" data-max-w="1440" data
 -max-h="1914" loading="lazy" data-optimized="true"/></picture><p><strong>
 Bio</strong></p><p>  Paulo Ramos is born from the womb of his mother\, Te
 rezinha Ramos de Jesus. He is an Afro-Brazilian visual artist\, performer
 \, actor\, and poet whose multidisciplinarywork spans video\, performance
 \, and poetry. His acclaimed poetry book\, Corpos d'├Īgua\, was published
  in 2023 in Brazil. And in 2026\, the book\, titled Bodies of Water\, wil
 l be released in the United States\, in English\, by NP-PRESS and Counter
 path Press. Ramos' compelling performance piece\, presented at the 12th A
 t First Sigh New Works Festival Indiana University and in venues across S
 ├Żo Paulo and Tepoztl├Īn\, gave rise to the thought-provoking videoperfor
 mance Bodies of Water: Threebuckets: a river\, a mangrow\, and a sean. Pa
 ulo Ramos is a Ph.D. in Social Science in Gender and Black Studies in PUC
 SP. Pontif├Łcia Universidade Cat├│lica de S├Żo Paulo\,Paulo Ramos continu
 es to explore and amplify the narratives of Afro-Brazilian identity.</p><
 p><strong>Abstract</strong></p><p>  Bodies of Water is an artistic perfor
 mance\, an academic confrontation grounded in the studies of Denise Ferre
 ira da Silva (2020)\, constructed through a poetic pathway in which the b
 ody becomes theoretical expansion. According to Denise Ferreira da Silva\
 , anticolonial art must be a confrontation.</p><p>  Bodies of Water: A Hy
 brid Cartography Flowing into an etnographyWE is part of my doctoral rese
 arch\, built from the memory\, orality\, and ancestry of Black women who 
 turn their daily notes into the reinvention of life in community. This re
 invention constitutes their intellectual production\, naming everything t
 hat inhabits space or emerges from the ways they experience the worldŌĆöo
 ne that is crossed by race\, class\, and the environmental. It concerns t
 he relationship between water and Black women-mothers as a way of thinkin
 g existence\, both as a site of escape and of resistance.</p><p>  Here\, 
 I propose to reflect from a fieldwork perspective that traverses my own s
 elfŌĆönot through an autoethnographic method\, but immersed in an etnogra
 phyWE\, a new theory in development for thinking about the women and the 
 waters that came before me.</p><p>  Thus\, Bodies of Water brings forth t
 ension\, discomfort\, and a critiCREATIVE approach developed alongside my
  research on my grandmother\, my mother\, my aunt\, and the watersŌĆöand 
 on environmental racism (Costa 2022\; Pacheco 2012). Bodies of Water is b
 odyŌĆōtimeŌĆōspace poetry. Above all\, it is confrontation. It is a profo
 und dialogue between the Black body and waterŌĆöliving elements\, yet con
 strained by the violence imposed by temporality.</p><p>  Ancestrality and
  Afropessimism are both present here\, navigating together in the same ve
 ssel through the currents of the Black body (Pinho 2021\; Smith 2015)\; b
 etween these two concepts\, ecology emerges as the missing link that conn
 ects them.</p><p><strong>About the Ostrom Workshop Research Series</stron
 g></p><p>  Learn about innovative research by Graduate Students and Visit
 ing Scholars as they advance the mission of the Ostrom Workshop\, buildin
 g upon the theme of governance to understand and address major societal p
 roblems.</p>
